<sn><md>#### I. Enstatite ($\mathrm{MgSiO_3}$)

**General Weathering &amp; Decomposition**
The chemical breakdown of enstatite ++under carbonation and hydration++ yields `talc and magnesium carbonate`:

$$\mathrm{MgSiO_3 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow Mg_3Si_4O_{10}(OH)_2\ (Talc) + MgCO_3}$$

**Further Reduction Pathways**
The ++intermediate weathering products++ break down and reduce further through the following sequential stages:

$$\begin{aligned} &amp;\text{Reduction of Talc:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{Mg_3Si_4O_{10}(OH)_2\ (Talc) + H_2O + CO_2 \longrightarrow SiO_2 + H_2O + MgCO_3} \\ &amp;\text{Leaching/Solubilization:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{MgCO_3 + H_2CO_3 \longrightarrow Mg(HCO_3)_2} \end{aligned}$$
</md></sn><sn><md>#### II. Hypersthene ($\mathrm{(Mg,Fe)SiO_3}$)

**1. Initial Weathering Stages**
Carbonation and hydration break down hypersthene into secondary silicate and carbonate compounds:

$$\mathrm{(Mg,Fe)SiO_3 + CO_2 + H_2O \longrightarrow Mg_3Si_4O_{10}(OH)_2\ (Talc) + MgCO_3 + FeCO_3}$$

**Subsequent Carbonate and Iron Alteration**

$$\begin{aligned} &amp;\text{Magnesium Carbonate Solubilization:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{MgCO_3 + H_2CO_3 \longrightarrow Mg(HCO_3)_2} \\ &amp;\text{Iron Carbonate Oxidation:} &amp;&amp; \mathrm{FeCO_3 + H_2O + O_2 \longrightarrow Fe(OH)_3 + CO_2} \end{aligned}$$

**Extreme Weathering Conditions**
Under extreme climatic pressures (high temperature followed by oxidation), the iron hydroxide undergoes advanced dehydration and oxidation phases to yield secondary iron oxides:

$$\mathrm{Fe(OH)_3 \xrightarrow{\text{high temp.}} FeO \xrightarrow{\mathrm{O_2}} Fe_2O_3\ (Haematite)}$$

In the presence of subsequent hydration, haematite alters to form limonite:

$$\mathrm{Fe_2O_3\ (Haematite) + H_2O \longrightarrow 2Fe_2O_3 \cdot 3H_2O\ (limonite)}$$</md></sn>